  <chapter><title>Introduction</title>
    <para>The development of Orca focused primarily on the
      requirements of its end users.  Orca's users may require
      non-visual access methods such as speech and/or braille and they
      may also require alternative visual access methods such as
      magnification.</para>

    <para>When designing Orca, its authors at Sun Microsystems engaged
      the user community from the start, soliciting feedback on questions
      such as the following:</para>

    <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
        <para>What tasks do they want to accomplish?</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>How do they accomplish these tasks?</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>What should the screen reader present to them?</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>What is the user experience like?</para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>

    <para>This book covers the user design of Orca, ranging from a
      poetic use of Cooper's "Persona" concept 
      <citation><xref linkend="cooper99" endterm="cooper99.abbrev"/>
      </citation>
      to the development of the end user requirements and default
      interaction styles for speech synthesis, braille, magnification, 
      and input devices.</para>

  </chapter>

